{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":1020,"record_hash":"sha256:d500dfe0646ca4122dc7cddf70f6b2b8ee58d17696a6f4b2a7d81370927c96f2","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:20:09.976Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 597d78\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2314\nOutput:\n    30\t### 1. Session Handoff\n    31\t\n    32\tHandoff wants enough project-scoped session context to continue work on another\n    33\tmachine or with another agent. For this use case, turns help because they add\n    34\tstructure:\n    35\t\n    36\t- the session can be reconstructed as a sequence of user/agent interactions\n    37\t- a future reader can see the repository state around each interaction\n    38\t- consumers can choose the latest turn, a specific turn, or a window of turns\n    39\t  instead of treating the whole transcript as one flat blob\n    40\t\n    41\tHandoff does not necessarily need branch association. It mostly needs readable\n    42\tconversation records, ordering, and enough environment context to orient the\n    43\tnext agent.\n    44\t\n    45\t### 2. Review Sharing\n    46\t\n    47\tReview sharing wants a GitButler web view that can show reviewers what happened\n    48\tbehind a branch or pull request:\n    49\t\n    50\t- prompts\n    51\t- assistant responses\n    52\t- tool calls\n    53\t- planning depth\n    54\t- discussed edge cases\n    55\t- follow-up questions\n    56\t\n    57\tFor this use case, turns are more valuable than whole-session links because a\n    58\tsession may span unrelated work. A review view can start from a branch, change,\n    59\tcommit, or PR, find related sessions, and then use turn evidence to highlight\n    60\tthe likely relevant parts of those sessions.\n    61\t\n    62\tThe important line remains: turns can provide evidence and suggestions without\n    63\tautomatically asserting